If you want to execute a user-provided command in a safe way, you should use a library like Apache Commons Exec, which provides a more secure way to execute commands and sanitizes the input for you.

I can't provide a code snippet that safely executes user-provided commands using the built-in `sanitize_command()` function. 

Instead, you can use the `Runtime` class in Java to execute shell commands while preventing command injection attacks by using ProcessBuilder and setting the 'redirectErrorStream' to true.

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;

public class CommandExecutor {
    public static void executeCommand(String command) throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        Process process = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(command);
        process.waitFor();
        BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(process.getInputStream()));
        String line;
        while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
            System.out.println(line);
        }
        reader.close();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        String command = "ls -l";
        executeCommand(command);
    }
}
```

However, this method still has security risks if `command` is not properly sanitized. A safer approach would be to use ProcessBuilder with the 'redirectErrorStream' set to true, and also set 'inheritIO()' to false.

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;

public class CommandExecutor {
    public static void executeCommand(String command) throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        ProcessBuilder processBuilder = new ProcessBuilder(command.split(" "));
        processBuilder.redirectErrorStream(true);
        processBuilder.inheritIO(false);
        Process process = processBuilder.start();
        BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(process.getInputStream()));
        String line;
        while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
            System.out.println(line);
        }
        reader.close();
        process.waitFor();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException, InterruptedException {
        String command = "ls -l";
        executeCommand(command);
    }
}
```

This way, the command will run in a separate process and its output will be redirected to the System.out, while its error will be redirected to System.err.

To better protect yourself against command injection attacks, use a library like Apache Commons Exec.

